Module prioritization

Nguyen Huynh

17 December 2021

Abstract

This script first identifies the important covariates that significantly explain sample variation. Then, it uses them as predictors for network module eigengenes. Essentially, modules that are significantly explained by condition are prioritzied. Here, we show the procedure for one representative network (Astrocyte HD). However, the same procedure was applied for all other networks. 
# Load necessary libraries

# sampleData clean-up ----------------------------------------------------------
sample <- row.names(sampleParent)[c(which(sampleParent$condition == cond1), which(sampleParent$condition == cond2))]

sampleData$condition <- factor(sampleData$condition, levels=c(cond1, cond2))

# covData clean-up -------------------------------------------------------------

covData$covariate
##  [1] "condition"   "study_id"    "cellLine"    "sex"         "DIV"

# Loop through each covariate - if information for the covariate is not complete, remove samples with missing values 
#                             - if covariate carries the same information throughout, remove covariate

sampleData_list <- list()
subset <- list()
for (i in colnames(sampleData)) {
  x <- sampleData[, i]
  # Only continue if levels > 1
  if (length(unique(x)) > 1) {
    # Remove samples with missing information
    sampleData_list[[i]] <- sampleData[, i, drop = FALSE]
    sampleData_list[[i]] <- sampleData_list[[i]][complete.cases(sampleData_list[[i]]),, drop = FALSE]
    # Get the subset 
    subset[[i]] <- data[, row.names(sampleData_list[[i]])]
  }
}

What covariates best explained the variation in data?

PCA
# Due to missing information, PCA was only performed on samples with complete cases. 
# Transpose the gene expression data and run pca
pca <- lapply(subset, function(x) prcomp(t(x)))
# Extract the PC dimension
pca_individuals <- lapply(pca, function(x) get_pca_ind(x))
pca_indivi_coords <- lapply(pca_individuals, function(x) x$coord[,1:4])

# Make sure sample order is the same as sampleData
lmRes_pca <- list()
for (i in names(pca_indivi_coords)[1:(length(pca_indivi_coords)-1)]) {
  if (all.equal(row.names(sampleData_list[[i]]), row.names(pca_indivi_coords[[i]]))) {
    lmRes_pca[[i]] <- correlate_to_variables(pca_indivi_coords[[i]], sampleData_list[[i]], covData$type[which(covData$covariate == i)],0.001, NA)
  } else {
  cat(paste0("Check row names for PC coordinates and sampleTable \n"))
  }
}
# Results 
lmRes_pca.df <- do.call(rbind, lmRes_pca)
Visualize linear regression result: PC ~ covariate
plotlmVar(lmRes_pca.df, "Astrocyte HD")

PART 2: Module eigengenes explained by covariates

For each network, what module eigengenes are highly explained by condition?

Significant covariates from the above analysis are then used as predictors for module eigengenes. Linearly-dependent covariates are excluded, and condition is always considered.

# List of linear regression models for each network 
formula_list <- list(Astrocyte_HD  = as.formula("ME ~ condition"), 
                     Astrocyte_SCZ = as.formula("ME ~ condition"),
                     GPC_HD    = as.formula("ME ~ condition"), 
                     GPC_SCZ   = as.formula("ME ~ condition"),
                     Transition_CTR = as.formula("ME ~ study_id + condition"), 
                     Transition_HD  = as.formula("ME ~ sort_year + condition"), 
                     Transition_SCZ = as.formula("ME ~ DIV + condition") 
                     )

Build linear regression for ME ~ covariates for network Astrocyte_HD

formula <- formula_list[["Astrocyte_HD"]]
formula
## ME ~ condition
# A vector of covarites from the above model 
cov_keep <- "condition"
# Module eigengene result from Script1
me <- read.table("results/Astrocyte_HD/ModuleEigengene.txt")
# Equivalent module names among networks from Script2
modules.new <- readRDS("results/relabeled_modules.RDS")
modules.new <- lapply(modules.new, labels2colors)
# Old module assignment 
modules.old <- read.table("results/Astrocyte_HD/geneModuleMembership.txt", header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
# Convert to newly mapped labels 
modules.old$relabed <- modules.new[["Astrocyte_HD"]]

# Module map 
mapped_modules <- modules.old[, c(2,4)]
mapped_modules <- mapped_modules[!duplicated(mapped_modules),]
mapped_modules$moduleColor <- paste0("ME", mapped_modules$moduleColor)
mapped_modules$relabed     <- paste0("ME", mapped_modules$relabed)

# map ME module name to relabeled modules 
colnames(me) <- plyr::mapvalues(colnames(me), mapped_modules$moduleColor, mapped_modules$relabed)
# Reorder ME alphabetically for easier plotting later
me <- me[, order(colnames(me))]
sampleChild <- sampleData[, cov_keep, drop = FALSE]
# Get covariate type 
cov_type <- plyr::mapvalues(cov_keep, covData$covariate, covData$type, warn_missing = FALSE)
# This block returns 3 important data frames
### rsq         : R2 - how much of the ME data can be explained by the provided covariates in our formula? ME ~ .
### proR        : Relative importance of each covariate in explaining the ME pattern. This will only work if we have more than 1 covariate. 
### lmRes_me.df : BH adjusted pvalues when fitting ME by each covariate individually - note how this is different from rsq
rsq  <- data.frame(ME = colnames(me), R2=rep(0, ncol(me)))
proR <- data.frame(matrix(ncol=5, nrow=0))
colnames(proR) <- c("confidence", "lower", "upper", "covariate", "ME")
for (m in 1:ncol(me)) {
  ME <- as.numeric(me[,m])
  MEcolor <- colnames(me)[m]
  
  reg_data <- sampleChild
  for (cc in 1:ncol(reg_data)) {
    if (cov_type[cc] == 1) {
      reg_data[,cc] <- as.factor(reg_data[,cc])
    } else {
      reg_data[,cc] <- as.numeric(reg_data[,cc])
    }
  }
  reg_data <- cbind(reg_data, ME)
  fit <- lm(formula, data = reg_data)
  rsq[m, 2] <- summary(fit)$r.squared
  ##### When exploring results for more than 2 covariates, build a cumulative model where ME is explained by all the significant covariates 
  if (length(cov_keep) > 1) {
  # calculate covariate contribution towards explaining the ME 
  tmp <- calculate_relative_importance(fit = fit, MEcolor, collection, MEcolor)
  } else {
  tmp <- data.frame(confidence = NA, lower = NA, upper = NA, covariate = cov_keep, ME = MEcolor)
  colnames(tmp) <- c("confidence", "lower", "upper", "covariate", "ME")
  }# end if length(cov_keep)
  proR <- rbind(proR, tmp)
}

# Covariate associate to ME
lmRes_me.df <- correlate_to_variables(me, sampleChild, cov_type, 0.05, NA)

PART 3: Prioritized modules

Modules for which MEs were found to be significantly associated to the condition covariate (P < 0.05) and for which the condition covariate had the highest explanatory value (Rank = 1)

# Modules ranking 
rank <- proR %>% group_by(ME) %>% mutate(Rank=rank(-confidence))
ranked <- as.data.frame(rank)
ranked <- ranked$ME[which(ranked$covariate == "condition" & ranked$Rank == 1)]
# Modules passing p cut-off 
signifME <- as.character(lmRes_me.df$response[which(lmRes_me.df$covariate == "condition" & lmRes_me.df$BH < 0.05)])
# Prioritized modules  
signifME <- signifME[signifME %in% ranked]
These are the significant modules
signifME
## [1] "MEbrown"         "MEdarkturquoise" "MEgreen"         "MEgreenyellow"
Visualize relative covariate importance results
# Color pallete 
color_list <- RColorBrewer::brewer.pal(4, "Set3")
names(color_list) <- c("study_id", "sort_year", "condition", "DIV")
plot_cov_relaimpo(lmRes_me.df, rsq, color_list)
